def: The act of praising unduly; excessive praise. Milton.
A second growth or crop, or (metaphorically) development. J. S.Mill.
Having two members; as, a bimembral sentence. J. W. Gibbs.
To blow together; to bring together; to collect;  to fusetogether; to join or weld; to consolidate.
To write one's name, alone or with other words, upon the backof (a paper), for the purpose of transferring it, or to secure thepayment of a
To eat into or away; to corrode; as, canker erodes the flesh."The blood . . . erodes the vessels." Wiseman.The smaller charge is more apt to . . . erode the gun. Am. Cyc.
A game, match, etc., open only to losers in early stages ofcontests.
Capable of being overcome or conquered; surmountable.Antipathies are generally superable by a single effort. Johnson.-- Su"per*a*ble*ness, n.-- Su"per*a*bly, adv.
An articular surface on the ilium of birds against which thegreat trochanter of the femur plays.
A covering for a person or thing; as, a nun's veil; a patenveil; an altar veil.
Showing condescending favor; assuming the manner of airs of asuperior toward another.-- Pat"ron*i`zing*ly, adv. Thackeray.
Smart; spruce; trim; nice. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.]
